The Ashfall Vigil is Kowloon's annual civic memorial for the Yen-Mak drowning and the black-rain years.
It is a civic ritual, not a religious one: the Neon Covenant's founding houses established it as institutional memory, distinct from the Temple Circle's liturgical practice.
The Vigil is observed as one hour of city-wide darkness — harbor lanterns extinguished, street beacons shuttered, Courier Lantern Office relay stations dark.
During the Vigil hour, the jade seal of the Jade Magistracy requires two magistrates to lift and carry, enforcing the co-authority principle even during symbolic ceremony.
No proclamation can be issued, no warrant executed, and no tribunal verdict delivered during the Vigil hour: all civic authority is suspended in collective remembrance.
The Vigil date is calculated from the lunar calendar used by the original delta settlements, not the solar calendar Midgaard standardized.
The Courier Lantern Office reads aloud from the founding census during the Vigil — the names of those registered in the city's earliest records, including the names recovered from Yen-Mak's survivor accounts.
The Black Ledger's sealed section contains Vigil-era depositions: testimony taken from survivors during the first five commemorations, before the political calculus shifted toward sealing records.
Reckoning faction members light counter-lanterns during the Vigil hour as a public protest, arguing that darkness without disclosure is grief used as a cover for concealment.
The Vigil is Kowloon's most politically contested civic ceremony: unanimous in observance, contested in meaning.
Travelers in Kowloon during the Vigil hour who do not know the custom frequently interpret the city-wide darkness as a power failure or a siege.

