Midgaard's registry recognizes the Ashfall Vigil as a Kowloon civic observance but does not hold a reciprocal commemoration.
The Temple of the Resounding Heart maintains memorial rolls from the Ashfall years, read annually on a date determined by Midgaard's solar calendar — approximately two weeks from Kowloon's Vigil date due to calendar differences.
The divergent dates are a minor but persistent source of inter-city friction: Kowloon's diplomatic missions to Midgaard during the Vigil period find that Midgaard's officials have already "done the memorial" on a different day.
Midgaard's Reckoning faction observes the Vigil's hour in solidarity with Kowloon's Reckoning faction — a cross-city political alignment that the Continuity faction on both sides monitors carefully.
Charter law does not require Midgaard to observe another city's civic ceremonies; charter law also does not prohibit it.
The Ash-and-Iron intake warrants from Midgaard's registry were processed on ordinary business days during the Vigil period in the years when Kowloon was founded — no suspension of operations occurred.

flags KOWLOON
---
The Vigil was designed by the founding houses to make institutional memory physically embodied: darkness is not symbolic but structural.
During the Vigil hour, Kowloon's gate mechanisms are locked open — a deliberate inversion of the usual security protocol, enacting the Neon Covenant's principle that shelter during disaster must be unconditional.
The jade seal's two-magistrate requirement during the Vigil is the most explicit architectural feature of the Covenant's distributed-authority principle: even in commemoration, no single official holds full power.
The sealed section of the Black Ledger was argued as a necessary protection during the third Vigil, when testimony deposited in the first two had become politically actionable against sitting magistrates.
The Courier Lantern Office maintains a separate Vigil register — names added each year of persons identified posthumously from Yen-Mak's population, recovered through genealogical research and comparative census work.
Kowloon's Neon Covenant framers intended the Vigil to prevent exactly what has happened: the moment has become contested between memory-factions rather than held in common.
The founding text states: "Let darkness be the ledger. Let each name read be an entry. Let no office be so urgent it cannot wait one hour for the dead."

