Kiess has no equivalent civic darkness ceremony, but the Syndic Council holds a closed session during the Vigil period to review the founding charter's sealed-warrant prohibition.
The session is administrative, not commemorative: it verifies that no sealed warrant has been issued in the preceding year, producing a formal negative attestation.
The negative attestation is Kiess's institutional equivalent of the Vigil — an annual confirmation that the documented failure mode has not recurred.
Kiess citizens in Kowloon during the Vigil participate in good standing; the ceremony's anti-warrant logic aligns with Kiess's charter doctrine.
Kiess's frontier risk philosophy views the Vigil's gate-opening protocol with qualified approval: unconditional shelter during disaster aligns with Kiess's disaster-planning doctrine, though the one-hour duration is considered more symbolic than operationally meaningful.
The Syndic Council's session notes from the Vigil period are among the few Kiess documents that explicitly cite Yen-Mak as a policy reference case.

