Rakuen has its own memorial rite for the Ashfall years — the Ash Requiem — but formally acknowledges the Vigil as the senior commemoration in the five-city network.
Rakuen's founding population included many who arrived from delta settlements that preceded Kowloon; their descendants hold the Vigil as partially their own history.
The Garden Ledger Clerks coordinate with Kowloon's Courier Lantern Office during the Vigil period to exchange census cross-references — matching founding-generation names across both registries.
Rakuen's Bloom Council observes the Vigil hour in a modified form: lanterns are dimmed but not extinguished, and the hour is used for a public reading of the Southmark Petition's opening text, linking Ashfall origin to annexation history.
The modified observance was politically negotiated: full darkness would imply Kowloon institutional primacy over Rakuen's own memorial practice, which the Compact Purist faction refused.
Rakuen's Assimilation League faction observes full darkness in solidarity with Kowloon, reading the gesture as a signal of institutional alignment.

