The Deltari communities of the delta observe the Vigil with additional practice not included in the Neon Covenant text: water-setting.
Water-setting is the placement of a small clay bowl of water on every threshold during the Vigil hour — the bowl left open to collect whatever falls during the night.
If rain falls, it is considered a year of sufficient grief. If nothing falls, the bowl is still left until dawn: empty grief is also grief.
The practice predates Kowloon's founding and was incorporated into Vigil observance by Deltari families without formal Covenant sanction.
The Jade Magistracy has noted the practice in census records as a "variant observance" without regulating it.
The water-setting tradition preserves the hydraulic-memory aspect of Deltari culture within the Vigil's institutional frame: Deltari bring their own form of record-keeping to the ceremony.
The clay bowls used are unglazed — deliberately: glazed bowls would resist the water, and the Deltari tradition requires contact, not repulsion.
